commentBody:
@Steven M. 

The rule is that an answer may not be repeated, except in the service of a theme.

This is the textbook example of that particular exception.

@Barry Ancona 

I too deleted a few options to go through a second pass before committing to entries. 

While it was quickly solvable, it wasn’t for lack of thought.

@Rachel 

Congratulations!

If you’re comfortable with most Wednesday puzzles, you should do fine with Sunday puzzles. They are bigger but not harder.

@Anita 
Yes, that’s a good observation about this puzzle setting the record for most repeats of a single entry word. But no one should forget the April Fools’ Day puzzle of 2002 which had 78 entries of which 39 were repeated. In that one the 15 letter-long vertical and horizontal spanners were of course repeats as well.

—  —  —  —

@BK 

I agree.  

After about the third one I laughed at every one.

@Wendy ahahahaha, I loved that! 





…
AAAAAAA

@Mike 

They're very picky.

Always finding faults.

@Sanjana 

FWIW, by design "earlier in the week" grids are always themed. In fact, only Friday and Saturday grids are billed as themeless puzzles -- though of course, there is always the possibility that the editors might choose to switch it up. 

If you haven't already, try Monday-Wednesday puzzles in the archives. Years worth of fun there!

@CCNY 

I keep a running list of POY candidates, and this puzzle is on it. 

But unless Puzzlemucker and Tito come back, there may not be any 2024 POY awards.

@David Holden - I had a family member who had a very serious problem with alcohol. 

On more than one occasion she was "section 12ed" (I believe that is the correct lingo...) to detox. Although she never went for a full rehab, as we wanted her to, in every case the place she was committed to was a REHAB center, which administered her detox treatments (after she got out of the emergency room). REHABs (a slangy term for these places) most certainly can perform detox. 

The clue and answer are fine as written. This is not a medical journal. It's a crossword.

@Pete 

I said last night that the puzzle seemed harder than usual on the whole for a Monday, and Barry Ancona agreed with me. 

It’s a rare day that Barry and I agree on anything, so it must be so.
